Functional traits are often discussed as useful metrics to help classify how plant communities impact ecosystem functions. They help us generalise across seemingly diverse species, and identify patterns among unrelated species. A growing body of literature is dedicated to identifying how plant traits help indicate or mediate the role a species has in providing a given ecosystem service. Root structures can affect soil carbon through the performance of exudates. Particular root systems can encourage or support particular microbial or other deocmpoers communities. The physical structure of wetland plants can also affect the amount of external carbon settles on the soil by physically slowing down flow, encouraging deposition of particulate organic matter.  The predominant mechanism, however, is contribution of authochthonous litter. A great deal has been added to the literature in the past decade to address the question of how do characteristics of vegetation impact their carbon storage and sequestration potential. it has been widely discussed that plants affect the rate and stability of soil organic carbon sequestration in a variety of ways. Plants contribute organic carbon through their biomass, which is deposited on soil surfaces and decomposed to a degree before potentially being assimilated into the soil. The degree to which a species contributes to this soil pool depends on both the volume and \'91decomposability\'92 of its litter. This \'91decomposability\'92 is typically referred to as litter quality. The literature typically correlates the same traits to affect both quantity and quality. The theory suggests that plants with higher productivity will contribute more litter to the soil, and so the theory dictates, also more organic carbon. The leaf economic spectrum hypothesised that aboveground plant material can be split along a single axis of variation between fast-growing, nutrient rich species characterised by low C:N versus slow-growing, nutrient-poor species characterised by high C:N. This is a useful dichotomy, especially as easy to measure leaf traits such as SLA and LDMC vary consistently with C:N ratio. Theory suggests that these same traits affect both productivity as well as indicate litter quality. This implies that species with higher carbon necessarily are more recalcitrant, or put another way, that all carbon is created equal, and that higher carbon implies higher recalcitrant carbon. \
\
