\cf0 \ulnone Litter collection\
In late austral summer 2016, we collected litter of 29 wetland plant species from ten sites in the southern portion of the Australian state of Victoria. Species cover a range of functional communities: graminoids (n = 14), forbs (n = 10), woody species (n = 5), and one bryophyte. All samples for a species was collected from a single site. When a target species was identified, we selected ten individuals at least 5 m apart from one another along a linear transect. Robust, well-grown individuals were selected for litter clippings, in accordance with trait measurement recommendations (Perez-Harguindeguy). Litter was stored in plastic bags with moist paper towels in dark coolers during transportation. A planned species list was organised before fieldwork commenced that informed selection of collection sites, whose species\'92 composition was known from prior work. This species list was modified slightly during litter collection due to availability of target species. \
\
Since the aim of this study was to examine the traits plant material that contributes to litter, any plant material that may end up as litter was included. For grass species such as Persicaria decipiens, for example, this included the culm, leaflets, as well as leaves. For graminoid species such as Juncus usitatus, this included the full stem of photosynthetic tissue, not including the seed head. In woody species such as Acacia dealbata, this included the twiglet hosting the leaves. We expect that this choice of plant part undoubtedly affected trait calculations, but is appropriate considering the objective. A full list of plant parts included per species is provided. \
