In order to use DTG data to estimate the mass fractions we must resolve the form of the independent curves included in the mixture model. In the biofuel field, these deconvolved curves are used to estimate kinetic thermal decay parameters. Many different models have been proposed to fit these kinetic curves, including Gaussian, Lorentzian, Weibull, the asymmetric bi-Gaussian, and the Frazer-Suzuki distributions. Symmetric curves such as the Gaussian and Lorentzian curves struggle because kinetic curves are often asymmetric. We used the four-parameter Fraser-Suzuki function in this study as it is highly flexible and has performed well when compared to empirically calculated kinetic parameters in the literature. The parameters associated with the Fraser-Suzuki function are height, skew, position, and width (ref equation). \
\
The mixture model (ref equation) was fit using functions made available in the R package \'91deconvolve\'92 (Windecker & Golding, GitHub). Starting values with reasonable upper and lower bounds are passed first through an optimiser, which improves selection of starting values for use in the non-linear modelling package, minpack.lm. The functions select whether to program three or four components based on whether a peak or shoulder is identified in the data below 500 K. This fourth peak represents very labile soluble carbohydrates such as sugars. These are common in XXX types of species, though not present in a significant portion in every curve. The three main carbon forms of interest, and for use as traits, were HC, CL, and LG. Identifying and quantifying the SC peak is manly useful to prevent assigning the mass lost in that interval to the wrong carbon form. Model parameterisation was verified using reference samples of glucose (to estimate soluble carbohydrates more widely), XXX (for hemicellulose), and cellulose. \
\
The Fraser-Suzuki function, due to its asymmetry, is useful for predicting kinetic curves and therefore useful for the deconvolution of parallel independent processes. The Fraser-Suzuki function is expressed as follows:\
\
$y = h\\ exp\\bigg\\\{-\\frac\{ln2\}\{s^2\}\\Big[ln\\Big(1 + 2s \\frac\{x- p\}\{w\}\\Big)\\Big]^2\\bigg\\\}$\
\
where T is the independent variable, in this case temperature, and the parameters h, s, p, and w are height, skew, position, and width of the curve, respectively. The rate expression ($d\\alpha/dT$) for a single curve can be written as follows: \
\
$\\frac\{d\\alpha\}\{dT\} = h\\ exp\\bigg\\\{-\\frac\{ln2\}\{s^2\}\\Big[ln\\Big(1 + 2s \\frac\{T- p\}\{w\}\\Big)\\Big]^2\\bigg\\\}$\
\
$\\alpha = \\frac\{M_0 - M_T\}\{M_0 - M_f\}$\
\
where $\\alpha$ is the conversion of mass from the start to the final temperature, given the initial: M is the dimensionless weight of the sample at initial temperature ($M_0$), at a given temperature ($M_T$), and at final temperature ($M_f$). Because we are assuming independent reactions by _n_ main pseudo components, mass loss rate is expressed as follows:\
\
$-\\frac\{dm\}\{dT\} = \\sum\\limits_\{i=1\}^n c_i\\frac\{d\\alpha_\{i\}\}\{dT\}$\
\
$c_i = M_\{0,i\} - M_\{char,i\}$\
\
$m = \\frac\{M_T\}\{M_0\}$\
\
where $c_i$ is the mass of pseudo component _i_ that is decayed, _i_ = 1, 2, 3, 4 refer to pseudo hemicellulose, pseudo cellulose, pseudo lignin, and pseudo soluble carbohydrates, respectively. $M_\{0,i\}$ and $M_\{char,i\}$ are the mass of the initial and final pyrolysis of the _i_-th component, respectively. When we introduce the Fraser-Suzuki function, the deconvolution can be expressed as: \
\
$-\\frac\{dm\}\{dT\} = \\sum\\limits_\{i=1\}^3 c_if_i(T)$\
\
where $f_i(T)$ represents the Fraser-Suzuki function with parameters $h_i$, $s_i$, $p_i$, and $w_i$. In total the model estimates 12 or 16 parameters, one of each of the former four for each of the three or four pseudo components. These are estimated using the nls.lm function as part of the minpack.lm package, which minimises the sum square of the vector returned by the function. The objective function used is the root mean square error of the predicted rate compared to the observed. \
\
The mass of each fraction in the overall mass loss within the cropped interval can be calculated by integrating under the curve of the component. This fraction can then be extrapolated to the mass fraction in the overall sample by incorporating mass cropped out by the lower and upper bounds and the remaining ash mass. \
