When we discuss vegetation contribution to soil carbon, we typically refer to litter quality as a magical catch-all to characterise litter residence in the soil. \
This work demonstrates that this is a false equivalence. Leaf traits SLA and LDMC do indeed vary predictably with elemental LNC and LCC, and therefore are useful indicators of volume of carbon contributed to the soil. However, these traits do not vary consistently with measures of carbon complexity, in this case measured as pseudo-hemicellulose, pseudo-cellulose, and pseudo-lignin. This work has demonstrated that we need to deepen our consideration of what affects litter quality as concerns soil carbon storage and sequestration. \
