A wetland approach - effect of plant parts\
Functional traits reflect both species\'92 response to environmental conditions, as well as mediate their relationship to various ecosystem functions. Functional trait research in general has mainly focussed on terrestrial systems, whose vegetation can be classified more simply: plant often have clear leaves separate to clear stem or woody material. It is less common in terrestrial systems to see plant material that has photosynthetic tissue along structural organs. In wetlands, not only must plants contend with temperature, precipitation, and soil conditions, there are also a range of hydrologic conditions to adapt to. Wetlands overall enjoy a much wider variation of environmental conditions than terrestrial systems, and in addition experience greater changes throughout the year. Plants in these environments must adapt to a wide range of conditions and other stressors including inundation, anoxia, drying out, and seasonal variation in nutrient and decomposer communities from runoff. The functional trait literature needs to begin to adapt to this variability by addressing trait-based research questions in wetland systems in particular. \
